docs.abstract: President Trump’s demand that Congress provide money to build a wall along the Southern border threatens to shut down portions of the government. Here’s why.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s demand that Congress provide money to build a wall along the Southern border threatens to shut down portions of the government. Here’s why.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Standing in the way of a resolution to the government shutdown is a wall. A still mostly hypothetical wall along large sections of the southern border intended to keep immigrants from entering the United States illegally. A wall that President Trump promised his supporters he would deliver once he was in the Oval Office. A wall that if not built, some conservatives say, could cost Mr. Trump his presidency.

headline.main: The Wall and the Shutdown, Explained
headline.print_headline: Explaining the Wall And Why It Derailed The U.S. Government

docs.abstract: Hundreds of American commandos and other troops are leaving West Africa even as terrorist attacks intensify and spread across the continent.
docs.snippet: Hundreds of American commandos and other troops are leaving West Africa even as terrorist attacks intensify and spread across the continent.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOUMBILA, Burkina Faso — President Trump has ordered most American troops to withdraw from Syria. He wants to bring home thousands more from Afghanistan. Now hundreds of United States commandos and other forces are leaving West Africa — despite an onslaught of attacks from an increasingly deadly matrix of Islamist fighters.

headline.main: Where Terrorism Is Rising in Africa and the U.S. Is Leaving
headline.print_headline: U.S. Pullback  In West Africa Worries Allies
